          "body": "The transition from dialogue to departure in 4:18-20 is swift and businesslike. Moses secures Jethro's blessing (4:18) — a detail that is not merely courteous but theologically significant: he does not act unilaterally; he honors the authority structure he lives within before leaving it. God then removes Moses's remaining fear: 'all the men who were seeking your life are dead' (4:19) — Pharaoh who sought to kill Moses after the Egyptian's death (2:15) has died in the forty years of Moses's absence. The path is clear. But before Moses reaches Egypt, God issues a remarkable briefing (4:21-23). He will harden Pharaoh's heart — a disclosure that the coming confrontation is not a contest between equals but a divine drama with a predetermined outcome (cf. Romans 9:17-18, where Paul cites this hardening as exhibit A of God's sovereign freedom). Then God gives Moses the first message to deliver to Pharaoh: 'Israel is My son, My firstborn. So I said to you, let My son go that he may serve Me; but you have refused to let him go. Behold, I will kill your son, your firstborn' (4:22-23). This is the most theologically packed sentence in the chapter. Israel's identity as God's *firstborn son* (*bekhor*) is a declaration of covenantal adoption — the same category of privileged heir with full claims on the father's house. The death of Pharaoh's firstborn, announced here before a single plague has fallen, is not a last resort but a predetermined counter-claim: you withhold My son; I will take yours. The entire plague sequence is implicitly contained in this announcement."
