          "body": "The most exegetically contested passage in the chapter — perhaps in all of Exodus — is 4:24-26. On the road to Egypt, 'the LORD met him and sought to put him to death' (4:24). The ambiguity of the pronoun 'him' has generated extensive discussion: is it Moses or his uncircumcised son? The mainstream of patristic and Reformation interpretation (followed by most modern evangelical scholars) understands Moses as the threatened party and his son's uncircumcision as the cause. Moses, the covenant mediator called to enforce the sign of the Abrahamic covenant on Israel, has himself neglected to administer that sign to his own son — almost certainly out of deference to Zipporah, who evidently found the rite repugnant (her exclamation, 'a bridegroom of blood,' reflects visceral disgust). The point is legally exact: you cannot credibly call a nation to covenant obedience while your own household stands outside the covenant sign. Zipporah acts — takes a flint, cuts the foreskin, throws it at Moses's feet — and the threat is withdrawn. Peter Davids notes in his commentary on related Pentateuchal texts that 'the covenant sign is not negotiable even when the covenant mediator is the one who has neglected it.' The passage is a severe pastoral warning embedded in a narrative of commission: God does not suspend His requirements for those He has called. The blood that satisfied His demand here is circumcision-blood — the same sign-of-the-covenant logic that will appear at the Passover (Ex. 12:13) in the form of blood on the doorpost."
