        "excerpt": "\"Now it came about at the lodging place on the way that the LORD met him and sought to put him to death.\"",
        "body": "No passage in Exodus generates more interpretive difficulty than these three verses. The pronoun 'him' (4:24) is ambiguous in Hebrew — it can refer to Moses or to Moses's son — and the identity of the one threatened has been debated since the second-century targums. The interpretive tradition that carries the most exegetical weight, followed by most evangelical commentators including Douglas Stuart (*Exodus*, NAC) and Brevard Childs, is that Moses himself is the target of divine judgment, because he has failed to circumcise his son — the covenant sign God commanded Abraham in Genesis 17:9-14.\n\nThe theological logic is exact and severe. Moses has just been commissioned to represent the God of the Abrahamic covenant before Pharaoh and Israel. The Abrahamic covenant's required sign — circumcision — marks covenant membership and covenant fidelity. A male who is not circumcised 'shall be cut off from his people; he has broken My covenant' (Genesis 17:14). Moses's son is uncircumcised, almost certainly because Zipporah had resisted the rite (her exclamation 'bridegroom of blood' suggests prior conflict over the custom). The commission to enforce covenant identity on a nation is incompatible with neglecting that sign in one's own household.\n\nZipporah's act is swift and decisive: she takes a flint (*tsor*, the same material used for covenant-circumcision knives throughout the Pentateuch, cf. Joshua 5:2), cuts off her son's foreskin, and throws it at Moses's feet (4:25). The phrase 'threw it at his feet' — combined with 'bridegroom of blood' — may indicate that the rite is being vicariously applied to Moses through the blood of his son: Zipporah is declaring that Moses stands under the covenant-blood her son has just shed. The LORD lets Moses alone (4:26) — the same verb (*raphah*) used for releasing a grip. The crisis resolves as abruptly as it began.\n\nThe pastoral weight of this passage is enormous. God does not suspend covenant obligation for those He has called. The one appointed to confront the world's most powerful ruler is himself confronted on the road. The blood that averts the judgment is covenant-sign blood — a typological pattern that will recur with full force at the Passover (Exodus 12:13), where blood on the doorpost is the difference between life and death in every household in Egypt. Peter Davids and other scholars of Pentateuchal theology note that the 'bridegroom of blood' formula is likely a legal formula acknowledging the life-price paid: Moses's life is purchased by the circumcision blood of his son.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Raphah* (let him alone, 4:26) — to relax a grip, to release. The same root used in 'Be still, and know that I am God' (Psalm 46:10). *Mulah* (circumcision, 4:26) — from *mul*, to cut off. *Dam* (blood) appears three times in vv. 25-26 — the repetition is deliberate and cultic: this is covenant-blood language, not merely biological description."
